  .docs.mn-layout-container
    mn-code.sh.
      # to install this module
      npm install --save mn-table-list

    p And bundle dependencies and main files in <strong>dist/</strong> with your preferred tool.

    h3 usage
    p Just use the class <strong class="attribute">.mn-table-list</strong> in a div, and inside of them, <strong class="attribute">.mn-item</strong>.
    mn-code.
      <div class="mn-table-list">
        <div class="mn-item">
          <span>John Snow</span>
          <span>snow@iknownothing.com</span>
        </div>
      </div>

    p If you want a header, just use the tag header before items, each title need be h1, h2, ... h6, e.g.
    mn-code.
      <div class="mn-table-list">
        <header>
          <h2>Name</h2>
          <h2>Email</h2>
        </header>
        <!-- .mn-item's here -->
      </div>

    h3 grid system
    p To setup the flow of itens, we use another module, called <a href="https://github.com/minimalist-components/mn-layout/">mn-layout</a>, but you can use whatever grid system that you wish.

    p In example below, we use the classes <strong>.mn-layout-column</strong>, <strong>.mn-layout-sm-row</strong> and <strong>.flex</strong> to define a flex direction to content.

    mn-code.html.
      <div class="mn-table-list">
        <header class="mn-layout-column mn-layout-sm-row">
          <h3 class="flex">Name</h3>
          <h3 class="flex">Email</h3>
        </header>

        <div class="mn-item mn-layout-column mn-layout-sm-row">
          <span class="flex">John Snow</span>
          <span class="flex">snow@iknownothing.com</span>
        </div>
      </div>


